         <abstract id="aspace_9d415d45968f1c60bd38a5c144f464a3">The papers consist of press releases, subject files, speeches, clippings, organization files and campaign ephemera from the presidential campaign conducted by Wendell Willkie in 1940.</abstract>
         <origination label="creator">
            <persname identifier="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n50019256" source="naf">
               <part>Willkie, Wendell L. (Wendell Lewis), 1892-1944</part>
            </persname>
         </origination>
    
      </did>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_5bd541bdb4ce3fb91f8a60983589fe77">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Accession received from Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, 6 October 1989.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_36d841738e1ad7cd2a92180177a4f061">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_0982932c21b10dcb2c57a72e966d6c84">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Wendell Willkie Presidential Campaign Papers. Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <bioghist id="aspace_0ad23b0f287df55cc2bc2ba4c6bcbd95">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Wendell Willkie received his A.B. from Indiana University in 1913. He was admitted to the Indiana bar in 1916, and practiced law in Indiana and New York. In 1940, Willkie became a candidate for president of the United States.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_ae69ca4dbd32fc820c1f8e4f538d0e52">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers consist of press releases, subject files, speeches, clippings, organization files and campaign ephemera from the presidential campaign conducted by Wendell Willkie in 1940.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_147b38c057e4092c3f50e59a5a546dab">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
